1. Read the data.

The California housing dataset includes one dependent variable (Value) and 8 explanatory variables. According to Latitude and Longitude, we split it into source and target, and then split the source dataset into different clusters, and split the target dataset into validation and test. Later we'll use linear regression to predice Value with variables except for Latitude and Longitude.

2. Smart Selection & Random Selection.

In the beginning, we random select 100 points from the source.

idx_initial = sample(1:nrow(Source), 100)
MSE_initial = pred_func(Source[,-c(6,7,10,11)], idx_initial , Validation[,-c(6,7,10,11)]); MSE_initial
## [1] 6801.477

For different seeds, we select the samples either smartly or randomly. There are 500 rounds in total. At each round, 10 samples are added to the training set, and the model is evaluated on the validation set.

layout(matrix(1:6,nrow = 3,byrow = TRUE))
for(seed in 1:6){
    step = 10
    l = selection(T = 500,st = 1,step = step, s = seed,
                  compare = 'previous',Source,Validation,idx_initial)
    p_selection(l$MSE,l$MSE_random,l$Clusters,n_cluster = n_cluster,
                  ylim = range(c(range(l$MSE),range(l$MSE_random))),
                  title = paste0('seed = ',seed ,',step = ',step
                                 ))
}

Is the difference between performance caused by the fact that "Smart selection uses less observations (with some have large weights)"?

get_difference = function(lst){
  sapply(2:length(lst), function(i){
    setdiff(lst[[i]],lst[[i-1]]) %>% length
  }) %>% unlist
}

layout(matrix(1:2,nrow=1))
hist(get_difference(l$idx),main = 'Smart Selection',xlab = 'Number of New Observations at Each Round',breaks = seq(0,11,1))
hist(get_difference(l$idx_random),main = 'Random Selection',xlab = 'Number of New Observations at Each Round',breaks = seq(0,11,1))

len1 = lapply(l$idx, function(x){x %>% unique() %>% length}) %>% unlist
len2 = lapply(l$idx_random, function(x){x %>% unique() %>% length}) %>% unlist
plot(1:length(l$idx),len1,type = 'l', xlab = 't',ylab = 'Number of Unique Observations',ylim = range(len2))
lines(1:length(l$idx),len2,col = 'red')

What if we use the closest ones at each round using the same number of unique observations with smart selection?

med = c(median(Source$Latitude),median(Source$Longitude))
med
## [1]   34.01 -118.15
distance = apply(Source[,c('Latitude','Longitude')], 1, function(x){
  sqrt((x[1] - med[1])^2 + (x[2] - med[2])^2)
})
MSE_closest = c()
closest_indices = list()
for(t in 1:500){
  indices = len1[t]
  closest_indices[[t]] = order(distance)[1:indices]
  
  loss = pred_func(Source[,-c(6,7,10,11)],closest_indices[[t]],
                              Validation[,-c(6,7,10,11)])
  
  MSE_closest = c(MSE_closest,loss)
}
plot(1:length(l$MSE),l$MSE,type = 'l',xlab = 't',ylab = 'MSE',cex.axis = 1,   cex.lab = 1.5,cex.main = 1.5,
       ylim = range(c(range(l$MSE),range(MSE_closest))) )
lines(1:length(MSE_closest),MSE_closest,col = 'red')
legend('topright',legend = c("Smart Selection","Closest"), lty = c(1,1),col = c('black','red'))

What if we use the closest ones at each round using the same number of unique observations with smart selection?
